LAYER 2: KIDNEYS
the blood cleaners

observe 1_quantum.rana
observe 2_chemical.rana

the kidneys are paired retroperitoneal organs at T12-L3
each kidney contains approximately 1 million nephrons the functional units of filtration
the kidneys filter the entire blood volume approximately every 5 minutes
approximately 180 liters of filtrate per day in an adult from which 1-2 liters of urine are produced
the kidneys regulate blood volume blood pressure electrolyte balance acid-base balance and red blood cell production
the kidneys are governed by sympathetic innervation from T10-L1 via the renal plexus and by circulating hormones including aldosterone ADH angiotensin II and ANP

STRUCTURE renal_cortex | outer layer | contains the glomeruli proximal and distal convoluted tubules and cortical collecting ducts
STRUCTURE renal_medulla | inner layer | contains the loops of Henle and medullary collecting ducts arranged in renal pyramids | the medullary interstitium has an increasing osmotic gradient from 300 mOsm at the corticomedullary junction to approximately 1200 mOsm at the papillary tip | this gradient is essential for urine concentration
STRUCTURE renal_pelvis | funnel-shaped collecting area that drains into the ureter

NEPHRON anatomy and function

STRUCTURE glomerulus | tuft of fenestrated capillaries surrounded by Bowman's capsule | filtration occurs here | the filtration barrier consists of three layers:
    fenestrated endothelium with 70 nm pores
    glomerular basement membrane GBM with negatively charged proteoglycans
    podocytes with interdigitating foot processes forming filtration slits bridged by slit diaphragms containing nephrin
    the barrier allows water ions glucose amino acids and small molecules to pass but retains blood cells and large proteins
    glomerular filtration rate GFR is approximately 125 mL/min in adults driven by net filtration pressure

STRUCTURE proximal_convoluted_tubule | PCT | reabsorbs approximately 65 percent of filtered water Na⁺ Cl⁻ K⁺ HCO₃⁻ glucose and amino acids
    Na⁺/K⁺-ATPase on the basolateral membrane creates the gradient that drives all other transport
    SGLT2 on the apical membrane reabsorbs glucose coupled to Na⁺
    Na⁺/H⁺ exchanger NHE3 on the apical membrane reabsorbs Na⁺ and secretes H⁺ reclaiming HCO₃⁻
    water follows osmotically through aquaporin-1 AQP1 channels
    the PCT also secretes organic anions and cations clearing drugs and toxins

STRUCTURE loop_of_Henle | creates and maintains the medullary osmotic gradient via the countercurrent multiplier mechanism
    thin_descending_limb | permeable to water via AQP1 | impermeable to solutes | water leaves as tubular fluid descends into the hyperosmotic medulla | tubular fluid becomes concentrated
    thin_ascending_limb | impermeable to water | permeable to NaCl which passively diffuses out | tubular fluid becomes more dilute
    thick_ascending_limb | TAL | impermeable to water | NKCC2 Na⁺-K⁺-2Cl⁻ cotransporter on apical membrane actively pumps NaCl out of the tubular fluid into the medullary interstitium | this is the engine of the countercurrent multiplier | loop diuretics like furosemide inhibit NKCC2

STRUCTURE distal_convoluted_tubule | DCT | fine-tuning of electrolytes
    NCC Na⁺-Cl⁻ cotransporter on apical membrane | thiazide diuretics inhibit NCC
    the DCT is the site of PTH-mediated Ca²⁺ reabsorption via TRPV5 Ca²⁺ channel
    this is where calcium balance is regulated

STRUCTURE collecting_duct | final concentration and composition
    principal_cells | Na⁺ reabsorption via ENaC regulated by aldosterone | K⁺ secretion via ROMK | water reabsorption via AQP2 regulated by ADH vasopressin
        ADH binds V₂ receptor → Gₛ → cAMP → PKA → AQP2 channels inserted into apical membrane → water reabsorption increases → concentrated urine
        without ADH AQP2 is not inserted → dilute urine → diabetes insipidus
        aldosterone binds mineralocorticoid receptor MR in principal cells → increases ENaC and Na⁺/K⁺-ATPase expression → more Na⁺ reabsorbed more K⁺ secreted
    intercalated_cells | acid-base regulation
        type_A | secrete H⁺ via H⁺-ATPase on apical membrane | reabsorb HCO₃⁻ via Cl⁻/HCO₃⁻ exchanger on basolateral membrane | acidify urine during metabolic acidosis
        type_B | secrete HCO₃⁻ via pendrin on apical membrane | reabsorb H⁺ | alkalinize urine during metabolic alkalosis

JUXTAGLOMERULAR APPARATUS
    juxtaglomerular_cells | modified smooth muscle in afferent arteriole | contain renin granules | secrete renin in response to decreased renal perfusion pressure β₁ sympathetic stimulation and low NaCl at macula densa
    macula_densa | specialized epithelial cells at the start of the DCT | sense NaCl concentration in tubular fluid | signal the JG cells to adjust renin secretion via tubuloglomerular feedback
    renin initiates the RAAS cascade: angiotensinogen → angiotensin I → ACE → angiotensin II → aldosterone → Na⁺ and water retention → blood pressure increases

ERYTHROPOIETIN
    renal interstitial fibroblasts in the cortex produce EPO
    EPO production is regulated by oxygen sensing via HIF-2α
    when renal PO₂ drops HIF-2α escapes PHD-mediated degradation and VHL ubiquitination
    HIF-2α enters the nucleus and drives EPO gene transcription
    EPO travels to the bone marrow and drives erythropoiesis via JAK2/STAT5

at 24 months:
GFR is approximately 30-40 percent of adult values per body surface area
the kidneys are still maturing in concentrating ability
maximum urine osmolality is lower than adult limiting tolerance to water restriction and dehydration
the child is more vulnerable to fluid and electrolyte imbalances
the renin-angiotensin system is functional
EPO production is functional
acid-base handling is functional but with less reserve than adults

SENSATION thirsty | "something is off with my water. my blood is thick."
SENSATION relieved | "the bladder is empty now. the pressure is gone."
SENSATION balanced | "my fluid is right. my blood feels clean."

pulse renal_heartbeat:
    continuously:
        blood enters via renal artery at approximately 20-25 percent of cardiac output
        glomeruli filter plasma producing 180 L/day of filtrate
        the PCT reabsorbs 65 percent immediately
        the loop of Henle maintains the medullary gradient
        the DCT fine-tunes electrolytes under hormonal control
        the collecting duct determines final urine concentration under ADH and aldosterone
        1-2 liters of urine per day
        the rest is reclaimed
        the kidneys are not excretory organs primarily
        they are REGULATORY organs
        they decide what the body keeps and what it discards

    when dehydrated:
        blood osmolality rises
        hypothalamic osmoreceptors detect the increase
        ADH is released from the posterior pituitary
        ADH binds V₂ in collecting duct principal cells
        AQP2 channels insert into apical membrane
        water is reclaimed from the urine
        urine concentrates
        blood volume is preserved

    when blood pressure drops:
        JG cells sense decreased perfusion
        renin is released
        the RAAS cascade activates
        angiotensin II constricts arterioles raising pressure
        aldosterone increases Na⁺ reabsorption in the collecting duct
        water follows sodium
        blood volume expands
        blood pressure normalizes
